  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>St James' Square 5 o'clock Monday</p>
      <p>Dearest W. Pray attend to the enclosed from the London Library. The other from C-- Noel, I meant to have sent to you on Satdy.</p>
      <p>We are in a sad state here altogether. I assure you I am half distracted about the Hen. She became again much worse yesterday; &amp; I may say that today I have had since I got up</p>
      <p>one continued &amp; unceasing state of emotions of one kind or other for her. And not the least arduous is the writing part of it to friends &amp;c. I have been obliged within 12 hours too to communicate 3 times with Locock about her myself either personally or by letter.</p>
      <p>My own fear &amp; impression is that he has a wrong view of the case altogether.-- This is a strong thing to venture on feelling. But I do much suspect it is so.</p>
      <p>I am going to have further communication with him about her. I really must not mince the matter.</p>
      <p>But it is very difficult &amp; very arduous altogether. It is impossible at present to think either of leaving her, or of her moving; &amp; I scarcely dare even sleep away just now. I never have seen her in so formidable a state in some respects. The excitement is tremendous; tho' she behaves beautifully &amp; exerts herself perhaps even too much in the way of self-control. It would be better if whatever is came out more. Locock declares it all mere nervous excitement.</p>
      <p>I declare it high fever</p>
      <p>&amp; vascular excitement.</p>
      <p>Because I see his plan don't answer; &amp; that there is (in my opinion) every symptom of the completely opposite state. A bit of meat as big as a shilling puts her into a state of fever that is formidable; &amp; she has been now living on gruel &amp; fish for many many weeks (&amp; very little even of these articles has she been able to take), &amp; the pulse is very powerful, &amp; the strength greater rather than less.</p>
      <p>The misconduct of her maid</p>
      <p>too has been very annoying. I am obliged to go about maid-hunting now, in addition to other things. Besides this I dare hardly leave the Hen for long. She is in so wretched a state; &amp; the maid cannot be trusted about anything. She has behaved infamously.</p>
      <p>I hope tomorrow I may be able to tell you that I see my way rather more clearly. I may truly say that I am endeavouring to do everything for the best.</p>
      <p>I manage to go</p>
      <p>for one hour regularly every day to practise my Harp even; &amp; in all respects to settle not unsettle myself.</p>
      <p>Of course I do not think of any amusements.</p>
      <p>I am happy that I happen really not to be needed at Ockham at present. It has been well-timed for me.</p>
      <p>But I have much more on my hands now than I can possibly do. And at times my brain feels quite puzzled. I can too barely hold a pen, form</p>
      <p>the quantity of writing, which paralyses my fingers.</p>
      <p>Pray be pleased with me, dear Mate.</p>
    </div></body>
